roit Free Press) Buy Photo CONNECT 9 COMMENT EMAIL MORE WXYZ-TV's JoAnne Purtan said goodbye Friday with a heartfelt message to her viewers of the past two decades. The Channel 7 veteran, whose contract was not renewed by the Detroit station, was choked up as she signed off for her final noon newscast. So was meteorologist Hally Vogel, who was delivering the weather for the noon news. \"JoAnne, you are a wonderful person, coworker, friend. And just to say you will be missed is a sore understatement,\" said Vogel, fighting back tears. \"We truly love you and are going to miss you.\" Broadcasting from Channel 7's glass booth inside the downtown Detroit Qube building, Purtan briefly thanked her friends and colleagues at the station and, in particular, all of the people watching at home. \"I thank you for inviting me into your homes for the last 20 years and, by the way, for all the heartfelt sentiments and well wishes on social media,\" she said. \"I want you to know I have read each and every comment on my Facebook page. I am truly grateful for, really, your love and support.\" Purtan posted March 9 on her Facebook page that she would be leaving the E.W. Scripps-owned television station because of corporate restructuring. Scripps has been making job cuts across its media properties. Her social media announcement was flooded with 5,300 Facebook responses representing a wave of disappointment and anger that Channel 7 was not renewing her contract. \"No way! What a mistake WXYZ! Joanne \u2014 you have always been my favorite \u2014 and the best female anchor \u2014 always a lady with class! WXYZ will lose me as a news viewer now,\" wrote Bevery Grau. An Emmy-winning anchor and reporter who juggled several duties at the station, Purtan also co-anchored \"The Now Detroit\" 4 p.m. newscast, served as a consumer reporter for \"Don't Waste Your Money\" segments and provided weekly profiles of local female entrepreneurs for \"Mom's a Genius\" segments. Also read: Maddox out at WXYZ following harassment suit Purtan's tenure at WXYZ began in 1998. As a prominent Detroit TV figure, she joined the family media tradition of her father, iconic Motor City radio deejay Dick Purtan. Earlier this month, her father shared his pride for his daughter's career and his feelings about her departure on his official Facebook page. \"This is a speed bump in a wonderful career \u2014 and her mother and I have no doubt that there will be much smooth sailing for her down the road,\" he wrote. Facebook | @Dick Purtan's Official Fan Page Dick Purtan's Official Fan Page And with her on-air goodbye, Purtan told viewers she would keep them posted about her future. In her March 9 Facebook post, she indicated she plans to remain in metro Detroit. \"I'm excited about what the future has to bring, but I will particularly miss this time together over the lunch hour every day,\" Purtan concluded. \"Thank you for watching and God bless.\" Contact Detroit Free Press pop culture writer Julie Hinds: 313-222-6427 or jhinds@freepress.com. CONNECT 9 COMMENT EMAIL MORE Share your feedback to help improve our site experience! From The USA TODAY NETWORK These sites are part of the USA TODAY NETWORK. Their content is produced independently from our newsrooms. More Stories", "highlightText": "", "highlightTitle": "", "language": "english", "external_links": [], "entities": {"persons": [{"name": "joanne purtan", "sentiment": "positive"}, {"name": "julie hinds", "sentiment": "none"}], "organizations": [{"name": "facebook email", "sentiment": "positive"}, {"name": "wxyz-tv", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "detroit free press", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "channel 7", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "wxyz", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "facebook", "sentiment": "none"}], "locations": [{"name": "detroit", "sentiment": "none"}]}, "rating": null, "crawled": "2018-03-24T08:11:49.002+03:00"}, {"thread": {"uuid": "57c5d70e66be840cfb64ab7870f9a56b8c21821d", "url": "http://omgili.com/ri/jHI