s and boys. This new stadium is a statement to PAL\u2019s commitment to the sports and programs we offer and the youth of Detroit.\u201d Read More: Dearborn mayor backs Ford's Detroit expansion The development hasn't been without its controversies, including concerns whether the new site would leave enough time for youth leagues and the general public and that the grass field would be replaced with turf. The Free Press previously reported that Richey told residents at least 51% of activities will be devoted to youths and that PAL will ensure there are daily public hours but will offer the field for private use during daytime hours when children are in school. PAL secured more than $20 million in donor gifts to build the 8,500-square-foot headquarters and banquet hall and the Willie Horton Field of Dreams presented by Meijer, according to a news release on PAL's website. Construction began in June 2016, and the old ballpark was razed in 2009. The Detroit Tigers last played there in 1999. \nTiger Stadium in 1999. (Photo: MARY SCHROEDER, DETROIT FREE PRESS) The ribbon-cutting ceremony on the field will feature speeches from Richey, Detroit Mayor Mike Duggan, Detroit Police Chief James Craig and former U.S. Sen. Carl Levin, according to a release. Events, including a private dinner, a donor wall unveiling, and a Paul W. Smith Live Remote, were planned for Friday. The sold-out dinner was to be the first event held in the new stadium and the first time the public will see the facilities, PAL stated in a news release. Tickets are still available for $75 for the MVP Afterglow from 9 p.m. to 11 p.m. Friday. The MVP Afterglow includes access to the facility and field, PAL said in a statement. Contact Hasan Dudar: hdudar@freepress.com.", "highlightText": "", "highlightTitle": "", "language": "english", "external_links": [], "entities": {"persons": [{"name": "willie horton", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "hasan dudar", "sentiment": "none"}], "organizations": [{"name": "faceboo